🔴 Core Difference
✅ First Solution
while(fast!=null && fast.next!=null){
    slow=slow.next;
    fast=fast.next.next;
}

ListNode midd = reverseList(slow);

👉 Here:

slow ends at middle (for odd) OR second middle (for even)
You reverse from slow itself
✅ Second Solution
while(fast.next!=null && fast.next.next!=null){
    slow=slow.next;
    fast=fast.next.next;
}

ListNode midd = reverseList(slow.next);

👉 Here:

slow stops one node before middle
You reverse from slow.next
So you skip the exact middle node (important for odd length)
🧠 Let’s Understand with Example
Example 1 (Odd length)
1 → 2 → 3 → 2 → 1
🔹 First Approach
slow → points to 3
Reverse from 3 → becomes:
1 → 2 → 3 ← 2 ← 1

Now comparing:

p1: 1 → 2 → 3
p2: 1 → 2 → 3

👉 Middle element 3 is compared with itself
✔ Works, but extra comparison

🔹 Second Approach
slow → points to 2 (before middle)
Reverse from slow.next (i.e., 3)

Reversed:

1 → 2 → 3 ← 2 ← 1

Now comparing:

p1: 1 → 2
p2: 1 → 2

👉 Middle 3 is skipped
✔ Cleaner & optimal

⚖️ Even Length Case
1 → 2 → 2 → 1
First Approach:
slow → second 2
reverse from there → OK
Second Approach:
slow → first 2
reverse from slow.next → also OK

👉 Both work fine for even length

🔥 Key Difference Summary
Aspect	First Code	Second Code
Middle handling	Includes middle	Skips middle
Reverse start	slow	slow.next
Comparisons	Extra comparison (odd case)	Minimal comparisons
Cleanliness	Slightly less clean	More standard ✅
